<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,438,2013]" pageId="9" pageNumber="196">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,762,788]" pageId="9" pageNumber="196">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Characterized by the following combination of characters: head yellow with dark red brown stripes (
<figureCitation box="[159,291,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1822,1846]" captionTargetBox="[224,1363,181,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-20@7.[224,1363,181,1798]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–27. Details of morphology. 11–17.—Head in anterior view. Scales = 0.5 mm. 18, 19.—Head in dorsal view. Scales = 0.5 mm. 20, 21.—First antennal segment. Scales = 0.1 mm. 22, 23.—Scutellum and mesoscutum. Scales 0.5 mm. 24, 25.—Hemelytron. Scales 0.5 mm. 26, 27.—Pronotum. Scales 0.5 mm. 11, 12, 18, 20, 22, 24, 26.—Valdasus favrei n. sp. Male holotype. 13, 19, 21, 23, 25, 27.—Valdasus ferrerai n. sp. Male holotype. 14.—Valdasus flavinotum (holotype); 15.—Valdasus henryi n. sp. (holotype); 16.—Valdasus schoenherri Stål, 1860 (♀, Brazil, USNM); 17.—Valdasus stygius (Distant) (lectotype)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4418539" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4418539/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="196">Figs 13, 19</figureCitation>
), yellow-brown antennal segment I with two red-brown rings (
<figureCitation box="[1011,1095,799,825]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,1822,1846]" captionTargetBox="[224,1363,181,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-20@7.[224,1363,181,1798]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 11–27. Details of morphology. 11–17.—Head in anterior view. Scales = 0.5 mm. 18, 19.—Head in dorsal view. Scales = 0.5 mm. 20, 21.—First antennal segment. Scales = 0.1 mm. 22, 23.—Scutellum and mesoscutum. Scales 0.5 mm. 24, 25.—Hemelytron. Scales 0.5 mm. 26, 27.—Pronotum. Scales 0.5 mm. 11, 12, 18, 20, 22, 24, 26.—Valdasus favrei n. sp. Male holotype. 13, 19, 21, 23, 25, 27.—Valdasus ferrerai n. sp. Male holotype. 14.—Valdasus flavinotum (holotype); 15.—Valdasus henryi n. sp. (holotype); 16.—Valdasus schoenherri Stål, 1860 (♀, Brazil, USNM); 17.—Valdasus stygius (Distant) (lectotype)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4418539" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4418539/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="196">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
), left paramere apical process without a distinct dorsobasal process (
<figureCitation box="[579,660,834,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–39" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1247,1271]" captionTargetBox="[206,1373,180,1224]" captionTargetId="figure-20@11.[206,1381,174,1224]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 34–39. Male genital structures. 34, 35.—Left paramere. 36, 37.—Right paramere. 38, 39.—Endophallus. 34, 36, 38.—Valdasus favrei n. sp. 35, 37, 39.—Valdasus ferrerai n. sp. Scale = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4418543" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4418543/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="196">Fig. 35</figureCitation>
) and endosoma possessing three sclerites (
<figureCitation box="[1140,1225,835,861]" captionStart="FIGURES 34–39" captionStartId="11.[151,264,1247,1271]" captionTargetBox="[206,1373,180,1224]" captionTargetId="figure-20@11.[206,1381,174,1224]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 34–39. Male genital structures. 34, 35.—Left paramere. 36, 37.—Right paramere. 38, 39.—Endophallus. 34, 36, 38.—Valdasus favrei n. sp. 35, 37, 39.—Valdasus ferrerai n. sp. Scale = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4418543" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4418543/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="196">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
